<article>
    <h1>CORPUS CHRISTI (R21)</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201009/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-09"><time>2020-10-09</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTOS: FILM&#xAD;GARDE CINE&#xAD;PLEXES, LIGHT&#xAD;HOUSE FILM DIS&#xAD;TRI&#xAD;BU&#xAD;TION,</span>
    </section>

    <p>115 minutes / Now show­ing</p>
    <p>In Poland, a convicted hood­lum fakes his way into a job as a vil­lage priest, a pow­er­ful fig­ure who hears con­fes­sions and gives com­fort to the dy­ing.</p>
    <p>In the tra­di­tion of comic satire, one might ex­pect the con­man to ex­pose the foibles of the Church and the gulli­bil­ity of the lo­cal yokels. There is some of that, but this movie largely avoids the smug re­li­gion-is-a-scam per­spec­tive.</p>
    <p>Daniel, played with sin­is­ter charm by Bar­tosz Bie­le­nia (left), gets what he wants: a pul­pit from which to blast his rad­i­cal take on the cat­e­chism. But he faces the grim re­al­ity of the vil­lage priest’s life – an ex­is­tence that can be marked by drudgery, de­pres­sion and, worst of all, lone­li­ness.</p>
    <p>Poland’s en­try in the Best In­ter­na­tional Fea­ture cat­e­gory of this year’s Academy Awards – the film made it to the fi­nal short­list – of­fers a por­trait of a spir­i­tual faker that never goes for the ob­vi­ous shots.</p>
    <p>WHERE: The Pro­jec­tor, Level 5 Golden Mile Tower,</p>
    <p>6001 Beach Road AD­MIS­SION: $13.50</p>
    <p>INFO: the­p­ro­jec­tor.sg</p>

